---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Meridian Guard vs Daily Loss Limits — What\'s the Difference?',
  description: 'Daily loss limits react after P&L damage has occurred. Meridian Guard focuses on behavioral risk signals before the damage compounds — rapid re-entry, stop manipulation, overtrading, rule-breaking. The two are complementary, not substitutes.',
  robots: { index: true, follow: true },
};

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: 'Should I use Meridian Guard instead of a daily loss limit?',
    a: 'No — use both. The daily loss limit is the non-negotiable floor: the worst-case financial ceiling on a session. Guard is the earlier warning layer that fires at behavioral thresholds before the financial limit is needed. They address different points in the same failure sequence.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What if Guard fires on a session where my strategy is actually working?',
    a: 'Guard fires when the trigger conditions you configured are met. If your rules are calibrated correctly to your own trading style, they should not fire during sessions where your behavior is within your normal plan. The PSI signal is compared against your own historical baseline, not a fixed population average.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can Guard act as a daily loss limit?',
    a: 'Yes — Guard\'s Session P&L Below trigger can be configured to end the session when P&L falls past a defined level, functioning as a software-enforced daily loss limit within NinjaTrader. The difference from a broker-enforced limit is that Guard can be configured with a buffer before the broker limit activates.',
  },
  {
    q: 'NinjaTrader already has account-level daily loss controls. Why do I need Guard?',
    a: 'NinjaTrader\'s native controls evaluate each order against a static threshold. They do not observe behavioral patterns across the session. Guard monitors whether entry frequency has doubled, whether stops are being widened, whether you are re-entering seconds after a stop-out. These patterns precede the financial limit being breached — and they are what Guard is designed to detect.',
  },
];

const faqSchema = JSON.stringify({
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: faqItems.map(({ q, a }) => ({
    '@type': 'Question',
    name: q,
    acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: a },
  })),
}).replace(/</g, '\\u003c');
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={faqSchema} />

  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">

    <header class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-3" style="color:#059669;">Comparison · NinjaTrader 8</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-zinc-900 leading-tight tracking-tight mb-6">
        Meridian Guard vs daily loss limits
      </h1>

      <!-- Quick Answer -->
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-emerald-200 px-6 py-5 mb-8" style="background:#f0fdf4;">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.12em] uppercase mb-2" style="color:#059669;">Quick answer</p>
        <p class="text-[15px] text-zinc-700 leading-relaxed">
          Daily loss limits react after P&amp;L damage has occurred. Meridian Guard focuses on behavioral risk signals before the damage compounds — rapid re-entry, stop manipulation, overtrading, and rule-breaking. The two are complementary, not substitutes.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-zinc max-w-none prose-p:text-[17px] prose-p:leading-[1.85] prose-headings:font-bold prose-headings:text-zinc-900 prose-h2:text-[1.35rem] prose-h2:mt-10 prose-h2:mb-3 prose-hr:border-zinc-200 prose-hr:my-10">

      <h2>What a daily loss limit does</h2>
      <p>
        A daily loss limit is a hard threshold: when your account drawdown reaches a defined amount, trading is suspended. At the broker level (Tradovate, Rithmic), this happens automatically. At the NinjaTrader platform level, account-level controls can be configured to block new orders when the limit is reached.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a necessary floor. Without it, a single bad session has no structural ceiling on how much damage it can produce.
      </p>
      <p>
        Its design is reactive. It responds to a completed financial outcome. By the time it fires, the behavioral sequence that drove the session off course has already fully played out.
      </p>

      <h2>What Meridian Guard does differently</h2>
      <p>
        Guard monitors the behavioral pattern of the session — not the financial outcome — and fires when behavioral thresholds are crossed, before any financial limit has been reached.
      </p>

      <!-- Comparison table -->
      <div class="not-prose overflow-x-auto my-8">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-zinc-200">
              <th class="text-left py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-zinc-900 w-1/3"></th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-zinc-500">Daily loss limit</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 font-semibold text-zinc-900">Meridian Guard</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-100">
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-500">When it fires</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-600">After P&L threshold is breached</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-zinc-900 font-medium">At behavioral trigger, before P&L limit</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-500">What it monitors</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-600">Cumulative P&L</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-zinc-900 font-medium">7 behavioral signals in real time</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-500">Responds to revenge entries?</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-600">Only if they breach the financial limit</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-zinc-900 font-medium">Yes — rapid re-entry after loss is a trigger</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-500">Responds to stop widening?</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-600">Only after loss is finalized</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-zinc-900 font-medium">Yes — Stop Manipulation signal fires at modification</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-500">Threshold type</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-600">Fixed dollar amount</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-zinc-900 font-medium">Calibrated to your own session history</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-500">Override protection</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-600">Broker-enforced (cannot override)</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-zinc-900 font-medium">Optional password lock</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-500">Use together?</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-zinc-600" colspan="2">Yes — Guard is the earlier warning; the limit is the hard floor if Guard fails</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>The window that neither covers alone</h2>
      <p>
        Consider a session that starts normally, produces a loss at midday, and then enters a phase of increasing entry frequency, progressive stop widening, and declining position quality. Each individual order is within the daily loss limit. No hard threshold has been crossed.
      </p>
      <p>
        But entry frequency has doubled from the trader's baseline. Stops are being moved progressively wider. PSI is in the Critical zone. The behavioral deterioration is fully underway — and neither the broker limit nor NinjaTrader's native controls have any basis to respond.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the window Guard is designed to operate in. It fires at the pattern, not the outcome. The limit catches the outcome if the pattern plays out fully.
      </p>

      <h2>Recommended configuration for NinjaTrader 8 traders</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Broker-level daily loss limit</strong> — active at the account level at your clearing firm; the non-negotiable floor</li>
        <li><strong>NinjaTrader account-level daily loss control</strong> — set slightly above the broker limit as a platform-layer redundancy</li>
        <li><strong>Meridian Guard behavioral triggers</strong> — configured to fire at behavioral thresholds before either financial limit is reached; for prop firm traders, Guard's P&amp;L trigger can be set with a buffer above the evaluation's maximum daily loss</li>
      </ol>

      <hr />

      <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <dl class="space-y-6 not-prose">
        {faqItems.map(({ q, a }) => (
          <div>
            <dt class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 text-[17px] mb-1">{q}</dt>
            <dd class="text-zinc-600 text-[16px] leading-relaxed">{a}</dd>
          </div>
        ))}
      </dl>

    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 pt-10 border-t border-zinc-100">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href="/pricing" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold text-white" style="background:#059669;">
          Start 7-day free trial
        </a>
        <a href="/guard" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold border border-zinc-300 text-zinc-700 hover:border-zinc-500 transition-colors">
          See Guard trigger types →
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 pt-8 border-t border-zinc-100">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-zinc-400 uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">About Meridian PSI</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-zinc-500 leading-relaxed">
        Meridian PSI is a real-time psychological stability monitor and behavioral risk-control add-on for NinjaTrader 8. It helps discretionary futures traders detect revenge trading, overtrading, stop-loss manipulation, oversizing, and rule violations, while Meridian Guard can enforce user-defined warnings, cooldowns, lockouts, and entry blocking before traders break their own rules.
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs text-zinc-400 mt-3">
        <em>Meridian is not affiliated with NinjaTrader LLC. NinjaTrader® is a registered trademark of NinjaTrader LLC. Trading involves substantial risk of loss. Results may vary.</em>
      </p>
    </div>

  </article>
</Layout>
